# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: color-scales-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] In color science, a **color gradient** (also known as a **color ramp** or a **color progression**) specifies a range of position-dependent colors, usually used to fill a region.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] In assigning colors to a set of values, a gradient is a continuous colormap, a type of color scheme.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] In computer graphics, the term swatch has come to mean a palette of active colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] An axial color gradient (sometimes also called a linear color gradient) is specified by two points, and a color at each point.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] The colors along the line through those points are calculated using linear interpolation, then extended perpendicular to that line.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] In digital imaging systems, colors are typically interpolated in an RGB color space, often using gamma compressed RGB color values, as opposed to linear.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] CSS and SVG both support linear gradients.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] A radial gradient is specified as a circle that has one color at the edge and another at the center.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] Colors are calculated by linear interpolation based on distance from the center.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] This can be used to approximate the diffuse reflection of light from a point source by a sphere.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] Both CSS and SVG support radial gradients.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] Conic or conical gradients are gradients with color transitions rotated around a center point (rather than radiating from the center).
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] Example conic gradients include pie charts and color wheels.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] Conic gradients are sometimes called "sweep gradients" (for example in the OpenType specification) or angular gradients.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] In vector graphics polygon meshes can be used, e.g., Adobe Illustrator supports *gradient meshes*.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] The appearance of a gradient not only varies by the color themselves, but also by the color space the calculation is performed in.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] A "linear" blend would match physical light blending and has been the standard in game engines for a long time.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] On the web, however, it has long been neglected for both color gradients and image scaling.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-gradient] Such a blend still has a subtle difference from one done in a perceptually-uniform color space.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] The term *image color transfer* is a bit of a misnomer since most common algorithms transfer both color and shading.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] There are two types of image color transfer algorithms: those that employ the statistics of the colors of two images, and those that rely on a given pixel correspondence between the images.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] In a wide-ranging review, Faridul and others identify a third broad category of implementation, namely user-assisted methods.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] An example of an algorithm that employs the statistical properties of the images is histogram matching.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] This is a classic algorithm for color transfer, but it can suffer from the problem that it is too precise so that it copies very particular color quirks from the target image, rather than the general color characteristics, giving rise to color artifacts.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Newer statistic-based algorithms deal with this problem.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] An example of such algorithm is one that adjusts the mean and the standard deviation of each of the source image channels to match those of the corresponding reference image channels.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] This adjustment process is typically performed in the Lαβ or Lab color spaces.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] A common algorithm for computing the color mapping when the pixel correspondence is given is building the joint-histogram (see also co-occurrence matrix) of the two images and finding the mapping by using dynamic programming based on the joint-histogram values.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] When the pixel correspondence is not given and the image contents are different (due to different point of view), the statistics of the image corresponding regions can be used as an input to statistics-based algorithms, such as histogram matching.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] The corresponding regions can be found by detecting the corresponding features.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Liu provides a review of image color transfer methods.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] The review extends into considerations of video color transfer and deep learning methods including Neural style transfer.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Color transfer processing can serve two different purposes: one is calibrating the colors of two cameras for further processing using two or more sample images, the second is adjusting the colors of two images for perceptual visual compatibility.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Color calibration is an important pre-processing task in computer vision applications.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Many applications simultaneously process two or more images and, therefore, need their colors to be calibrated.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Examples of such applications are: Image differencing, registration, object recognition, multi-camera tracking, co-segmentation and stereo reconstruction.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Other applications of image color transfer have been suggested.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] These include the co-option of color palettes from recognised sources such as famous paintings and the use as a further alternative to color modification methods commonly found in commercial image processing applications such as ‘posterise’, ‘solarise’ and ‘gradient’.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] A web application has been made available to explore these possibilities.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] The use of the terms *source* and *target* in this article reflects the usage in the seminal paper by Reinhard et al.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] However, others such as Xiao and Ma reverse that usage and indeed it seems more natural to consider that the colors from a *source* image are directed at a *target* image.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Adobe use the term *source* for the color reference image in the Photoshop *Match Color* function.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] Because of this confusion over terminology, some software releases may incorporate incorrect functionality.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-mapping] To minimise further confusion, it may be good practice henceforth to utilise terms such as *input image* or *base image* or *content image* and *color source image* or *color palette image* respectively.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] In color theory, a **color scheme** is a combination of 2 or more colors used in aesthetic or practical design.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Aesthetic color schemes are used to create style and appeal.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Colors that create a harmonious feeling when viewed together are often used together in aesthetic color schemes.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Practical color schemes are used to inhibit or facilitate color tasks, such as camouflage color schemes or high visibility color schemes.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Qualitative and quantitative color schemes are used to encode unordered categorical data and ordered data, respectively.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Color schemes are often described in terms of logical combinations of colors on a color wheel or within a color space.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Harmonious color schemes are designed to accomplish an aesthetic color task and enhance color harmony.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] They do not represent any underlying variable.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The color scheme of a logo is typically purely aesthetic.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A color scheme in marketing is referred to as a trade dress and can sometimes be protected by trademark or trade dress laws, as is the pink color of Owens Corning fiberglass.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Any color that lacks strong chromatic content is said to be unsaturated, achromatic, or near neutral.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Pure achromatic colors include black, white, all grays and beiges; near neutrals include browns, tans, pastels, and darker colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Near neutrals can be of any hue or lightness.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] For example, the "Achromatic" use of a white background with black text is an example of a basic and commonly default color scheme in web design.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Black and white have long been known to combine well with almost any other colors; black decreases the apparent *saturation* or *brightness* of colors paired with it, and white shows off all hues to equal effect.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Monochromatic color schemes may contain all the colors (tints, tones, and shades) of a single hue, i.e. the base hue modified by the addition of black, gray and white.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] As a result, the energy is more subtle and peaceful due to a lack of contrast of hue.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A complementary color scheme comprises two colors that combine to form gray, i.e. they are on opposite sides of the color wheel.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Fully saturated complementary colors maximize color contrast.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A *split-complementary* (also called compound harmony) color scheme comprises three colors, namely a base color and two colors that are 150 degrees and 210 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The split-complementary color scheme has the same sharp visual contrast as the complementary color scheme but has less pressure.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Analogous color schemes (also called dominance harmony) are groups of colors that are adjacent to each other on the color wheel, with one being the dominant color, which tends to be a primary or secondary color, and two on either side complementing, which tend to be tertiary.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This usually translates to a three-color combination consisting of a base color and two colors that are 30 degrees and 330 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A analogous color scheme tends to have a consistent temperature, comprising only warm or only cool colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] An analogous color scheme creates a rich, semi-monochromatic look.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] However, the scheme also lacks contrast and is less vibrant than complementary schemes.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Red, reddish-orange, orange, yellow-orange is one example of a set of analogous colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A *near-analogous* color scheme comprises three colors, namely a base color and two colors that are 60 degrees and 300 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The near-analogous color scheme has the same consistency as the analogous color scheme but has more contrast in comparison.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] One example of a near-analogous color scheme would be red, yellow, and magenta.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] An *accented analogous* color scheme adds the complementary color of an analogous color scheme as the accent color, used to create a dominant color grouping of three similar colors accented with the direct complement (or the near complement) of one of them.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The complementary accent color creates an interesting contrast against the dominant color grouping.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This scheme is frequently used to put a warm accent color with a cool analogous color palette, or a cool accent color with a warm palette.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The triadic color scheme is a three-color combination consisting of base color and two colors that are 120 degrees and 240 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This scheme is popular among artists because it provides sharp visual contrast while maintaining balance and color richness.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The triadic scheme is not as contrasting as the complementary scheme, but it is easier to accomplish balance and harmony with these colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The tetradic (also called double complementary) color scheme uses four colors arranged into two complementary color pairs.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This scheme is hard to harmonize and requires a color to dominate or subdue the colors; if all four colors are used in equal amounts, the color scheme may look unbalanced.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The hexadic (also called triple complementary, or double triadic) color scheme is a six-color combination consisting of base color and five colors that are 60, 120, 180, 240 and 300 degrees apart from the base color.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This color scheme uses six colors which are arranged into three complementary color pairs, or it could be seen as two triadic color schemes or two near-analogous color schemes—or adding a complementary pair to a rectangular tetradic color scheme.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] An example of this color scheme is red, yellow, green, cyan, blue, and magenta.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Practical color schemes combine colors outside typical aesthetic media and context for purely practical reasons, generally focusing on maximizing or minimizing contrast, instead of color harmony.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] The most common practical color scheme is black-and-white, which generally maximizes contrast.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This may be used for black text on a white background or prison uniforms.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Enhancing contrast against a background motivates some practical color schemes, such as high visibility color schemes, while inhibiting contrast against a background motivates others, as in camouflage.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Qualitative color schemes represent categorical variables, where the possible values of the variable are discrete and unordered.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] An example of a categorical variable is U.S. states, which has 50 unordered values.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A qualitative color scheme is generally also called a color code.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Generally, the number of colors in a qualitative color scheme is equal to the number of possible values for the categorical variable, where each value is encoded to one color.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] However, the number of total colors can be decreased by encoding each value with multiple colors, as in the 25-pair color code, which encodes 25 values using only 10 colors, by assigning each value a color each from group A and group B, each consisting of 5 colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] A qualitative color scheme can be designed similarly to a harmonious color scheme.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] However, the goal of a qualitative color scheme is to solve a comparative color task rather than an aesthetic color task, so enhancing color difference between the colors in the color scheme is generally more important than color harmony.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Quantitative schemes are fundamental to Thematic maps, charts, data science, spreadsheets, and other tools which use graphical means to visualize quantitative data.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] They are common in heat maps, choropleths and other forms of visualization.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] These color schemes can be categorized into different classes, depending on the nature of the underlying data.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Scientifically derived color schemes (or scientific color maps) seek to improve on traditional color schemes (spectral schemes such as *rainbow* or *jet*) by incorporating a uniform color gradient and color blind accessibility.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] In the 1990s, Cynthia Brewer performed a number of experiments on various color schemes for data visualization in maps, especially working with those with color blindness.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Eventually, this work led to a palette of several dozen color schemes designed to be reproducible on multiple devices and usable by the color blind, which was collected into an interactive tool known as ColorBrewer in 2002.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] This palette quickly gained wide acceptance due to its reliable usability by non-experts, and has become a standard built into GIS and mapping software and other visualization tools.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Connotative color schemes use colors that reference a specific cultural meaning.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Red and green color schemes are connotative of Christmas.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] In some countries, a red, white and blue color scheme connotes the Flag of the United States.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] In hotel room designs, the relationship between preferences of color schemes and gender was detected.
[src:color-scales-viz/color-scheme] Male guests tend to prefer masculine color schemes, while female guests favor feminine color schemes.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] As colorfulness, chroma, and saturation are defined as attributes of perception, they can not be physically measured as such, but they can be quantified in relation to psychometric scales intended to be perceptually even—for example, the chroma scales of the Munsell system.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] On a Munsell hue page, lines of uniform saturation thus tend to radiate from near the black point, while lines of uniform chroma are vertical.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] The naïve definition of saturation does not specify its response function.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] In the CIE XYZ and RGB color spaces, the saturation is defined in terms of additive color mixing, and has the property of being proportional to any scaling centered at white or the white point illuminant.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] However, both color spaces are non-linear in terms of psychovisually perceived color differences.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] It is also possible — and sometimes desirable — to define a saturation-like quantity that is linearized in term of the psychovisual perception.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] In the CIE 1976 LAB and LUV color spaces, the unnormalized **chroma** is the radial component of the cylindrical coordinate CIE LCh (lightness, chroma, hue) representation of the LAB and LUV color spaces, also denoted as CIE LCh(ab) or CIE LCh for short, and CIE LCh(uv).
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] The chroma in the CIE LCh(ab) and CIE LCh(uv) coordinates has the advantage of being more psychovisually linear, yet they are non-linear in terms of linear component color mixing.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] And therefore, chroma in CIE 1976 Lab and LUV color spaces is very much different from the traditional sense of "saturation".
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] Another, psychovisually even more accurate, but also more complex method to obtain or specify the saturation is to use a color appearance model like CIECAM02.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] Here, the **chroma** color appearance parameter might (depending on the color appearance model) be intertwined with e.g. the physical brightness of the illumination or the characteristics of the emitting/reflecting surface, which is more sensible psychovisually.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] The CIECAM02 chroma $C,$ for example, is computed from a lightness J in addition to a naively evaluated color magnitude $t.$ In addition, a colorfulness M parameter exists alongside the chroma $C.$ It is defined as $M=CF_{B}^{0.25},$ where $F_{L}$ is dependent on the viewing condition.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] The saturation of a color is determined by a combination of light intensity and how much it is distributed across the spectrum of different wavelengths.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] The purest (most saturated) color is achieved by using just one wavelength at a high intensity, such as in laser light.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] If the intensity drops, then as a result the saturation drops.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] To desaturate a color of given intensity in a subtractive system (such as watercolor), one can add white, black, gray, or the hue's complement.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] Various correlates of saturation follow.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] The CIE has not formally recommended this equation since CIELAB has no chromaticity diagram, and this definition therefore lacks direct connection with older concepts of saturation.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] Nevertheless, this equation provides a reasonable predictor of saturation, and demonstrates that adjusting the lightness in CIELAB while holding (*a**, *b**) fixed does affect the saturation.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] This definition is inspired by experimental work done with the intention of remedying CIECAM97s's poor performance.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] M is proportional to the chroma $C,$ thus the CIECAM02 definition bears some similarity to the CIELUV definition.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] Saturation is also one of three coordinates in the HSL and HSV color spaces.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] However, in the HSL color space saturation exists independently of lightness.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] That is, both a very light color *and* a very dark color can be heavily saturated in HSL; whereas in the previous definitions—as well as in the HSV color space—colors approaching white all feature low saturation.
[src:color-scales-viz/colorfulness] Different color spaces, such as CIELAB or CIELUV may be used, and will yield different results.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The concept behind **true color** can help in understanding false color.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] An image is called a *true-color* image when it offers a natural color rendition, or when it comes close to it.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] This means that the colors of an object in an image appear to a human observer the same way as if this same observer were to directly view the object: A green tree appears green in the image, a red apple red, a blue sky blue, and so on.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] This true-color image shows the area in actual colors, e.g., the vegetation appears in green.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] , red and green spectral bands mapped to RGB – this image shows vegetation in a red tone, as vegetation reflects most light in the near infrared.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Absolute true-color rendering is impossible.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The result of a metameric failure would be for example an image of a green tree which shows a different shade of green than the tree itself, a different shade of red for a red apple, a different shade of blue for the blue sky, and so on.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Color management (e.g. with ICC profiles) can be used to mitigate this problem within the physical constraints.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] spectral bands (blue / green, green and near infrared).
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] In contrast to a true-color image, a **false-color image** sacrifices natural color rendition in order to ease the detection of features that are not readily discernible otherwise – for example the use of near infrared for the detection of vegetation in satellite images.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] While a false-color image can be created using solely the visual spectrum (e.g. to accentuate color differences), typically some or all data used is from electromagnetic radiation (EM) outside the visual spectrum (e.g. infrared, ultraviolet or X-ray).
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The choice of spectral bands is governed by the physical properties of the object under investigation.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] As the human eye uses three spectral bands (see trichromacy for details), three spectral bands are commonly combined into a false-color image.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] At least two spectral bands are needed for a false-color encoding, and it is possible to combine more bands into the three visual RGB bands – with the eye's ability to discern three channels being the limiting factor.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] In contrast, a "color" image made from one spectral band, or an image made from data consisting of non-EM data (e.g. elevation, temperature, tissue type) is a *pseudocolor image* (see below).
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] For true color, the RGB channels (red "R", green "G" and blue "B") from the camera are mapped to the corresponding RGB channels of the image, yielding a "RGB→RGB" mapping.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] For false color this relationship is changed.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The simplest false-color encoding is to take an RGB image in the visible spectrum, but map it differently, e.g.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] For traditional false-color satellite images of Earth a "NRG→RGB" mapping is used, with "N" being the near-infrared spectral band (and the blue spectral band being unused) – this yields the typical "vegetation in red" false-color images.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] False color is used (among others) for satellite and space images: Examples are remote sensing satellites (e.g.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Landsat, see example above), space telescopes (e.g. the Hubble Space Telescope) or space probes (e.g.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Some spacecraft, with rovers (e.g. the Mars Science Laboratory *Curiosity*) being the most prominent examples, have the ability to capture approximate true-color images as well.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Weather satellites produce, in contrast to the spacecraft mentioned previously, grayscale images from the visible or infrared spectrum.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] : The left image shows vegetation density and the middle image presence of water (greens / blue for wet soil and red for dry soil).
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] , as is particularly the case in fields 120 and 119 (indicated by red and yellow pixels).
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] These fields were due to be irrigated the following day.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] is false-color, as can be inferred from the pink stars.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] , the first picking up light in the frequency of sulfur ions (arbitrarily assigned to the color red), the second hydrogen (green), and the third oxygen ions (blue).
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The actual color of the nebula is unknown, but if viewed at a distance making the 1-light-year-long "pillars" similarly visible, it would probably appear as a nearly uniform brownish grey to human eyes.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] False color has a range of scientific applications.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Spacecraft often employ false-color methods to help understand the composition of structures in the universe such as nebula and galaxies.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The frequency of light emitted by different ions in space are assigned contrasting colors, allowing the chemical composition of complex structures to be better separated and visualised.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The image of the Eagle Nebula above is a typical example of this; the Hydrogen and Oxygen ions have been assigned green and blue respectively.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The large amounts of green and blue in the image show that there is a large amount of Hydrogen and Oxygen in the nebula.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] On 26 October 2004, the NASA/ESA Cassini-Huygens spacecraft captured a false-color image of Titan, Saturn's largest moon.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The image was captured in Ultraviolet and Infrared wavelengths, both invisible to the human eye.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] In order to provide a visual representation, false color techniques were used.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The infrared data was mapped to red and green colors, and ultraviolet mapped to blue.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A **pseudocolor** image (sometimes styled **pseudo-color** or **pseudo color**) is derived from a grayscale image by mapping each intensity value to a color according to a table or function.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Pseudo color is typically used when a single channel of data is available (e.g. temperature, elevation, soil composition, tissue type, and so on), in contrast to false color which is commonly used to display three channels of data.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Pseudocoloring can make some details more visible, as the perceived difference in color space is bigger than between successive gray levels alone.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] On the other hand, the color mapping function should be chosen to make sure the lightness of the color is still monotonic, or the uneven change would make it hard to interpret levels, for both normal and colorblind viewers.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] One offender is the commonly used "rainbow" palette, with a back-and-forth change in lightness.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A typical example for the use of pseudo color is thermography (thermal imaging), where infrared cameras feature only one spectral band and show their grayscale images in pseudo color.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] in the foreground and a traditional building in the background.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] There is a color to temperature key on the right.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] using pseudocolor encoding – yellow/white indicates hot and red/violet indicates cool.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Areas reaching 3,000 °F (1,650 °C) can be seen in yellow.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Another familiar example of pseudo color is the encoding of elevation using hypsometric tints in physical relief maps, where negative values (below sea level) are usually represented by shades of blue, and positive values by greens and browns.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] , showing ocean floor in shades of blue and land in greens and browns.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] There is a color to elevation key on the bottom.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] with hypsometric tints of red for the highest points and purple for the lowest.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Depending on the table or function used and the choice of data sources, pseudocoloring may increase the information contents of the original image, for example adding geographic information, combining information obtained from infrared or ultra-violet light, or other sources like MRI scans.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] This image shows compositional variations of the Moon overlaid as pseudo color.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A grayscale MRI of a knee – different gray levels indicate different tissue types, requiring a trained eye.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A pseudocolor MRI of a knee created using three different grayscale scans – tissue types are easier to discern through pseudo color.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A further application of pseudocoloring is to store the results of image elaboration; that is, changing the colors in order to ease understanding an image.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A **choropleth** is an image or map in which areas are colored or patterned proportionally to the category or value of one or more variables being represented.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The variables are mapped to a few colors; each area contributes one data point and receives one color from these selected colors.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Basically, it is density slicing applied to a pseudocolor overlay.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A choropleth map of a geographic area is thus an extreme form of false color.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] While artistic rendition lends to subjective expression of color, Andy Warhol (1928–1987) has become a culturally significant figure of the modern art movement by creating false-color paintings with screen printing techniques.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Some of Warhol's most recognizable prints include a replication of Marilyn Monroe, her image based on a film frame from the movie *Niagara*.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The subject was a sex symbol and film noir starlet whose death in 1962 influenced the artist.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] A series of prints were made with endearment but expose her persona as an illusion through his assembly line style of art production which are non-erotic and slightly grotesque.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] Using various ink color palettes, Warhol immersed himself in a process of repetition that serves to compare personas and everyday objects to the qualities of mass production and consumerism.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] The colors of ink were selected through experimentation of aesthetics and do not correlate to false-color rendering of the electromagnetic spectrum employed in remote sensing image processing.
[src:color-scales-viz/false-color] For years the artist continued screen printing false-color images of Marilyn Monroe, perhaps his most referenced work being *Turquoise Marilyn* which was bought in May 2007 by a private collector for 80 million US dollars.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In computer science, a **lookup table** (**LUT**) is an array that replaces runtime computation of a mathematical function with a simpler array indexing operation, in a process termed as ***direct addressing***.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The savings in processing time can be significant, because retrieving a value from memory is often faster than carrying out an "expensive" computation or input/output operation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The tables may be precalculated and stored in static program storage, calculated (or "pre-fetched") as part of a program's initialization phase (*memoization*), or even stored in hardware in application-specific platforms.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables are also used extensively to validate input values by matching against a list of valid (or invalid) items in an array and, in some programming languages, may include pointer functions (or offsets to labels) to process the matching input.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] FPGAs also make extensive use of reconfigurable, hardware-implemented, lookup tables to provide programmable hardware functionality.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] LUTs differ from hash tables in that, to retrieve a value v with key k , a hash table would store the value v in the slot $h(k)$ where h is a hash function i.e. k is used to compute the slot, while in the case of LUT, the value v is stored in slot k , thus directly addressable.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Before the advent of computers, lookup tables of values were used to speed up hand calculations of complex functions, such as in trigonometry, logarithms, and statistical density functions.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In ancient (499 AD) India, Aryabhata created one of the first sine tables, which he encoded in a Sanskrit-letter-based number system.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Early in the history of computers, input/output operations were particularly slow – even in comparison to processor speeds of the time.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] It made sense to reduce expensive read operations by a form of manual caching by creating either static lookup tables (embedded in the program) or dynamic prefetched arrays to contain only the most commonly occurring data items.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Despite the introduction of systemwide caching that now automates this process, application level lookup tables can still improve performance for data items that rarely, if ever, change.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables were one of the earliest functionalities implemented in computer spreadsheets, with the initial version of VisiCalc (1979) including a `LOOKUP` function among its original 20 functions.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Microsoft Excel includes multiple specialized lookup functions, with `VLOOKUP` for vertical lookup (as in a traditional lookup book), `HLOOKUP` for horizontal lookup, and (since 2019) `XLOOKUP` for outputting multiple output columns at once.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Although the performance of an LUT is a guaranteed $O(1)$ for a lookup operation, no two entities or values can have the same key k .
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] When the size of universe U —where the keys are drawn—is large, it might be impractical or impossible to be stored in memory.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] For a trivial hash function lookup, the unsigned raw data value is used *directly* as an index to a one-dimensional table to extract a result.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] For small ranges, this can be amongst the fastest lookup, even exceeding binary search speed with zero branches and executing in constant time.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] One discrete problem that is expensive to solve on many computers is that of counting the number of bits that are set to 1 in a (binary) number, sometimes called the *population function*.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] For example, the decimal number "37" is "00100101" in binary, so it contains three bits that are set to binary "1".
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The above implementation requires 32 operations for an evaluation of a 32-bit value, which can potentially take several clock cycles due to branching.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] It can be "unrolled" into a lookup table which in turn uses trivial hash function for better performance.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The bits array, *bits_set* with 256 entries is constructed by giving the number of one bits set in each possible byte value (e.g.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Sum of ones in each byte of the integer can be calculated through trivial hash function lookup on each byte; thus, effectively avoiding branches resulting in considerable improvement in performance.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In data analysis applications, such as image processing, a lookup table (LUT) can be used to transform the input data into a more desirable output format.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] For example, a grayscale picture of the planet Saturn could be transformed into a color image to emphasize the differences in its rings.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In image processing, lookup tables are often called **LUT**s (or 3DLUT), and give an output value for each of a range of index values.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] One common LUT, called the *colormap* or *palette*, is used to determine the colors and intensity values with which a particular image will be displayed.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In computed tomography, "windowing" refers to a related concept for determining how to display the intensity of measured radiation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] A classic example of reducing run-time computations using lookup tables is to obtain the result of a trigonometry calculation, such as the sine of a value.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Calculating trigonometric functions can substantially slow a computing application.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The same application can finish much sooner when it first precalculates the sine of a number of values, for example for each whole number of degrees (The table can be defined as static variables at compile time, reducing repeated run time costs).
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] When the program requires the sine of a value, it can use the lookup table to retrieve the closest sine value from a memory address, and may also interpolate to the sine of the desired value, instead of calculating by mathematical formula.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables can thus be used by mathematics coprocessors in computer systems.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] An error in a lookup table was responsible for Intel's infamous floating-point divide bug.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Functions of a single variable (such as sine and cosine) may be implemented by a simple array.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Functions involving two or more variables require multidimensional array indexing techniques.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The latter case may thus employ a two-dimensional array of **power[x][y]** to replace a function to calculate **xy** for a limited range of x and y values.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Functions that have more than one result may be implemented with lookup tables that are arrays of structures.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] As mentioned, there are intermediate solutions that use tables in combination with a small amount of computation, often using interpolation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Pre-calculation combined with interpolation can produce higher accuracy for values that fall between two precomputed values.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] This technique requires slightly more time to be performed but can greatly enhance accuracy in applications that require it.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Depending on the values being precomputed, precomputation with interpolation can also be used to shrink the lookup table size while maintaining accuracy.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] While often effective, employing a lookup table may nevertheless result in a severe penalty if the computation that the LUT replaces is relatively simple.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Memory retrieval time and the complexity of memory requirements can increase application operation time and system complexity relative to what would be required by straight formula computation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The possibility of polluting the cache may also become a problem.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Table accesses for large tables will almost certainly cause a cache miss.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] This phenomenon is increasingly becoming an issue as processors outpace memory.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] A similar issue appears in rematerialization, a compiler optimization.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In some environments, such as the Java programming language, table lookups can be even more expensive due to mandatory bounds-checking involving an additional comparison and branch for each lookup.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] There are two fundamental limitations on when it is possible to construct a lookup table for a required operation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] One is the amount of memory that is available: one cannot construct a lookup table larger than the space available for the table, although it is possible to construct disk-based lookup tables at the expense of lookup time.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] The other is the time required to compute the table values in the first instance; although this usually needs to be done only once, if it takes a prohibitively long time, it may make the use of a lookup table an inappropriate solution.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] As previously stated however, tables can be statically defined in many cases.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Most computers only perform basic arithmetic operations and cannot directly calculate the sine of a given value.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] However, this can be expensive to compute, especially on slow processors, and there are many applications, particularly in traditional computer graphics, that need to compute many thousands of sine values every second.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] A common solution is to initially compute the sine of many evenly distributed values, and then to find the sine of *x* we choose the sine of the value closest to *x* through array indexing operation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] This will be close to the correct value because sine is a continuous function with a bounded rate of change.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Unfortunately, the table requires quite a bit of space: if IEEE double-precision floating-point numbers are used, over 16,000 bytes would be required.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] We can use fewer samples, but then our precision will significantly worsen.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] One good solution is linear interpolation, which draws a line between the two points in the table on either side of the value and locates the answer on that line.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] This is still quick to compute, and much more accurate for smooth functions such as the sine function.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Linear interpolation provides for an interpolated function that is continuous, but will not, in general, have continuous derivatives.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] For smoother interpolation of table lookup that is continuous **and** has continuous first derivative, one should use the cubic Hermite spline.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] When using interpolation, the size of the lookup table can be reduced by using *nonuniform sampling*, which means that where the function is close to straight, we use few sample points, while where it changes value quickly we use more sample points to keep the approximation close to the real curve.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] For more information, see interpolation.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] Storage caches (including disk caches for files, or processor caches for either code or data) work also like a lookup table.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] A single (fast) lookup is performed to read the tag in the lookup table at the index specified by the lowest bits of the desired external storage address, and to determine if the memory address is hit by the cache.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] When a hit is found, no access to external memory is needed (except for write operations, where the cached value may need to be updated asynchronously to the slower memory after some time, or if the position in the cache must be replaced to cache another address).
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In digital logic, a lookup table can be implemented with a multiplexer whose select lines are driven by the address signal and whose inputs are the values of the elements contained in the array.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] These values can either be hard-wired, as in an ASIC whose purpose is specific to a function, or provided by D latches which allow for configurable values.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] An *n*-bit LUT can encode any *n*-input Boolean function by storing the truth table of the function in the LUT.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] This is an efficient way of encoding Boolean logic functions, and LUTs with 4-6 bits of input are in fact the key component of modern field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which provide reconfigurable hardware logic capabilities.
[src:color-scales-viz/lookup-table] In some systems, polynomials may also be defined in place of lookup tables for these calculations.
